# HIBISCUS CARE GUIDE 🌺  
(Heavy flowering ornamental — Nutrient & pruning responsive)

---

## 🌺 Plant Nature & Behaviour Model

Hibiscus is a **continuous flowering, high-energy ornamental shrub**.

Core traits:

✔ Extremely heavy feeder  
✔ Loves sunlight (CRITICAL)  
✔ Responds dramatically to pruning  
✔ Flowers on NEW GROWTH  
✔ Sensitive to potassium deficiency  
✔ Highly pest-prone  
✔ Rapid growth cycles

Critical mental model:

Leaves build energy → Energy produces buds → Buds produce flowers.

Weak nutrition = Leaf plant  
Balanced nutrition = Flower machine

---

## ☀️ LIGHT REQUIREMENT (NON-NEGOTIABLE)

Hibiscus LOVES sun.

✔ Minimum 6–8 hrs direct sunlight  
✔ Full sun ideal

Low light symptoms:

✔ Few/no flowers ❌  
✔ Long weak stems  
✔ Large leaves but no buds  
✔ Bud drop

Sunlight = Primary flowering trigger.

---

## 🌱 SOIL MANAGEMENT

Ideal soil:

✔ Well-draining  
✔ Rich organic matter  
✔ Loose & aerated  
✔ Never compacted

---

### ✅ ORGANIC FOUNDATION (IMPORTANT)

Every 30–45 days:

✔ Vermicompost → 300–500 g  
✔ Cow Manure → Light handful

Why:

✔ Sustained nutrient base  
✔ Improves flowering consistency  
✔ Enhances soil biology

Optional booster:

✔ Humic Acid Drench

Dose:
2–3 g/L

Frequency:
Every 30–45 days

Why:

✔ Root stimulation  
✔ Improves nutrient uptake

---

## 💧 WATERING STRATEGY

Golden rule:

✔ Moist — NOT soggy  
✔ Avoid complete drying  
✔ Avoid constant wet soil

Typical rhythm:

✔ Every 2–3 days (heat dependent)

Classic hibiscus failure:

✘ Overwatering → Yellow leaves → Root stress  
✘ Underwatering → Bud drop

Hibiscus dislikes stress instability.

---

## 🧪 FERTILIZER PROGRAM (FLOWERING DOMINANT)

Hibiscus = Heavy feeder + Continuous bloomer.

---

### 🌿 GENERAL GROWTH PHASE

✔ NPK 19:19:19

Dose:
1 g/L

Frequency:
Every 7–10 days (YES — heavy feeder)

Why:

✔ Sustains rapid metabolism  
✔ Leaf & shoot health  
✔ Bud formation support

Hibiscus consumes nutrients FAST.

---

### 🌺 FLOWERING PHASE (MOST IMPORTANT)

✔ SOP 00:00:50 (Potassium Engine)

Dose:
1 g/L

Frequency:
Every 10–14 days

Why:

✔ Bud formation  
✔ Flower size  
✔ Bloom longevity  
✔ Colour intensity  
✔ Bud retention

CRITICAL INSIGHT:

Potassium deficiency = MOST COMMON flowering problem.

---

### 🦴 CALCIUM SUPPORT (IMPORTANT)

✔ Calcium Nitrate

Dose:
1 g/L

Frequency:
Every 20–30 days

Why:

✔ Bud strength  
✔ Prevents bud drop  
✔ Improves stem strength

Do NOT mix with SOP.

Alternate cycles.

---

### 🌿 MAGNESIUM BOOST (VERY IMPORTANT)

✔ Epsom Salt

Dose:
1 g/L

Frequency:
Every 20–30 days

Why:

✔ Deep green leaves  
✔ Better photosynthesis  
✔ More bud production

Magnesium deficiency is VERY common in hibiscus.

---

### 🔬 MICRONUTRIENTS (CRITICAL)

✔ Micronutrient Mix

Frequency:
Every 30–45 days

Why:

✔ Prevents chlorosis  
✔ Sustains flowering rhythm  
✔ Bud formation support

Deficiency symptoms:

✔ Yellow leaves with green veins  
✔ Small flowers  
✔ Poor bud formation

---

### 🌊 SEAWEED EXTRACT (EXCELLENT FOR FLOWERS)

Dose:
2–3 ml/L

Frequency:
Every 20–30 days

Why:

✔ Flower stimulation  
✔ Stress buffering  
✔ Root vigor  
✔ Bud retention

---

## 🐛 PEST MANAGEMENT (HIBISCUS = PEST MAGNET)

Common pests:

• Aphids  
• Mealybugs  
• Whiteflies  
• Thrips  
• Spider mites (VERY COMMON)  

Hibiscus attracts EVERYTHING.

---

## 🚨 SPIDER MITES (MOST DANGEROUS & COMMON)

Symptoms:

✔ Tiny yellow speckles  
✔ Fine webbing  
✔ Leaf dullness  
✔ Leaf drop

Cause:

✔ Dry heat + low humidity

---

### ✅ PREVENTIVE BASELINE (NON-NEGOTIABLE)

✔ Neem Oil

Dose:
3–5 ml/L + Wetting agent

Frequency:
Every 7–10 days

YES — Hibiscus needs aggressive prevention.

---

### ✅ SAP SUCKING PESTS

✔ Thiamethoxam (if infestation visible)

Targets:

✔ Aphids  
✔ Whiteflies  
✔ Mealybugs

Use only when needed.

---

### ✅ THRIPS / FLOWER DAMAGE

✔ Indoxacarb / Chlorantraniliprole (rotate)

---

## 🍄 DISEASE MANAGEMENT

Common diseases:

✔ Leaf spot  
✔ Powdery mildew  
✔ Root rot (watering issue)

---

### ✅ PREVENTIVE

✔ Hexaconazole

Frequency:
Every 30–45 days (humid season)

---

### ✅ CURATIVE

✔ Azoxystrobin + Mancozeb

Use when spotting visible.

---

## ✂️ PRUNING STRATEGY (THIS CONTROLS FLOWERING)

Hibiscus flowers on NEW GROWTH.

No pruning = Aging wood = Fewer flowers.

---

### ✅ WHEN TO PRUNE

✔ After flowering flush  
✔ Whenever plant becomes leggy  
✔ Structural pruning seasonally

Hibiscus LOVES pruning.

---

### ✅ PRUNING OBJECTIVES

✔ Stimulate new shoots  
✔ Increase flowering points  
✔ Control height & shape  
✔ Remove weak growth

---

### ✅ WHAT TO REMOVE

✔ Long leggy branches  
✔ Weak thin stems  
✔ Crossing branches  
✔ Inward-growing shoots  
✔ Dead/diseased wood

Goal:

✔ Dense bushy canopy  
✔ Multiple growing tips

More tips = More flowers.

---

### ✅ PRUNING INTENSITY

✔ Moderate to heavy pruning OK  
✔ Hard cutback tolerated  
✔ Very forgiving plant

---

### ✅ CUTTING TECHNIQUE

✔ Cut above outward-facing node  
✔ Slight angled cut  
✔ Clean sharp pruner  
✔ No stubs

Wrong pruning → Dieback / ugly structure.

---

## 🌺 FLOWERING FAILURE INSIGHTS

No flowers → Low sunlight / Excess nitrogen / Low potassium  
Bud drop → Water stress / Potassium deficiency / Calcium imbalance  
Small flowers → Potassium deficiency  
Yellow leaves → Magnesium / micronutrient deficiency / Overwatering  
Leaf drop → Root stress / Spider mites  
Lots of leaves, few flowers → Excess nitrogen

---

## ⚠️ HIGH-IMPACT FAILURE POINTS

Hibiscus struggles mostly from:

1) Insufficient sunlight (MOST COMMON)  
2) Potassium deficiency (EXTREMELY COMMON)  
3) Magnesium deficiency  
4) No pruning  
5) Overwatering  
6) Spider mite infestation  
7) Excess nitrogen → Leafy plant

---

## 🎯 OPTIMAL CARE PHILOSOPHY

Hibiscus thrives on:

✔ Full sunlight dominance  
✔ Frequent feeding cycles  
✔ Potassium-rich flowering support  
✔ Regular magnesium supplementation  
✔ Periodic micronutrients  
✔ Aggressive neem prevention  
✔ Bold pruning strategy  
✔ Stable watering rhythm

Hibiscus is a metabolic furnace.

Feed it → It explodes with flowers.

Starve it → It sulks silently.

